3gz.title: Underlying set
3gz.text:
[summary: What do a [-3gd], a [-3rb], and a [ topological space] have in common? Each is a [-3jz] with some structure built on top of it, and in each case, we call the set the *underlying set*.]


What do a [-3gd], a [-3rb], and a [ topological space] have in common? Each is a [-3jz] with some structure built on top of it, and in each case, we call the set the *underlying set*. %%note: A group is a set with an [3h7 operation], a poset is a set with an [3dt ordering], and a topological space is a set with a collection of subsets that satisfy a [ certain property].%%

###Algebraic structures###

An [3gx algebraic structure] is a set equipped with operators that follow certain laws, such as a [3gd group], which is a pair $(X, \bullet)$ where $X$ is a [3jz set] and $\bullet$ is an operator that follows certain laws. Given an algebraic structure,  we can simply throw away the operators and recover the set ($X$, in this case), which is known as the "underlying set" of the structure.

The underlying set is sometimes known as the "carrier set." Some algebraic structures have more than one underlying set; for example, a vector space is an algebraic structure built out of a [481 field] of scalars and a [3h2 commutative group], in which case the term "underlying set" is ambiguous.
